{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Donald Bannerman Macleod | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1887|07|21|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Doyleston]], New Zealand | death_date = {{Death date and age|1972|03|08|1887|07|21|df=y}} | death_place = [[Wellington]], New Zealand | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | other_names = | residence = New Zealand | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = [[Molecular physics]] | workplaces = [[University of Canterbury|Canterbury University College]] | patrons = | alma_mater = Canterbury University College | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 1922 | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = [[Coleridge Farr]] | influenced = | awards = [[Hector Medal]] (1940) | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | spouse = | children = }} '''Donald Bannerman Macleod''' (21 July 1887 – 8 March 1972) was a New Zealand [[molecular physicist]].
==Early life and education== Born at [[Doyleston]], near [[Christchurch]], in 1887,<ref>{{cite news | url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=CHP18870810.2.87.6.1 | title=Births | date=10 August 1887 | work=The Press | accessdate=18 August 2014 | page=2}}</ref> Macleod studied at [[University of Canterbury|Canterbury University College]], graduating with an [[Master of Arts|MA]] with first-class honours in chemistry in 1910.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://shadowsoftime.co.nz/university15.html |title=NZ university graduates 1870–1961: Ma |date= |website= |publisher= |accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=CHP19230512.2.132.20 |title=N.Z. University |work=The Press |date=12 May 1923 |page=5 |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref>
==Academic career== Following his graduation, Macleod was appointed as a lecturer in physics at Canterbury and worked there until his retirement in 1953 as an associate professor. He had a research collaboration with Professor [[Coleridge Farr]] from 1911 to 1936.<ref name="Chronicle">{{cite journal |date=April 1972 |title=Death of Dr Macleod |url=http://www.canterbury.ac.nz/irm/graphics/Registry/Chronicle%20-%20Tender%20Accepted%20for%20Registry%20at%20Ilam%20-%20April%201972%20-%20Vol%207,%20No%202.pdf |journal=Chronicle |publisher=University of Canterbury |volume=7 |issue=2 |accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> In 1922 Macleod was awarded a [[DSc]] from Canterbury University College.<ref name="DSC">{{cite news |url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=CHP19220508.2.94 |title=N.Z. University: official examination results |work=The Prress |page=10 |date=8 May 1922 |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref>
He was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of New Zealand]] in 1935<ref name="Chronicle"/> and in 1940 he was awarded the society's [[Hector Medal]] for his work in the field of molecular physics.<ref>{{cite journal |year=1940–41 |title=Minutes of the annual meeting, 22nd May, 1940 |url=http://rsnz.natlib.govt.nz/volume/rsnz_70/rsnz_70_00_000070.html |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of New Zealand |publisher= |volume=70 |issue= |page=II |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref>
